Linear Regression or Linear Model(LM) is used to predict outcome variable(y)-Crime in our dataset- on the basis of one/multiple predictor variables(x). The overall quality of the linear regression fit can be assessed using RSE, R2, and F-statistic. In the above model we see the RSE is 209, R2 is 0.7, and F-statistic is 8.4.

RSE or model sigma, corresponds to the prediction error. The lower the RSE the best the model fits to our data. R2 ranges from 0 to 1 and represents the proportion of variation in the outcome variable. The closer it is to 1, the larger proportion of the variability in the outcome. R2 in our model is pretty good. F-statistics that gives the overall significance of the model. 8.4 producing p.value of 3.539e-07 p<0.05 shows statistical high significance.

#Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) measures the model prediction error.(the avg difference of the obsesereved values of the outcome and the predicted values by the model)

print(sprintf("RMSE for Model_1 = %0.2f", sigma(model_1) ))
## [1] "RMSE for Model_1 = 209.06"

#predicting crime rate for the given test data

predict(model_1, testdata)
##        1 
## 155.4349

Here we are predicting an outcome variable (y)-Crime- on the basis of multiple distinct predictor variables(x).Therefore, this is a multiple linear regression. The predicted value of 155.43 is way below the minimum of crime rate within our dataset. Although the model seemed to be good, the prediction is not. This might be due to overfitting or the fact that all predictors were count for.

Note: when building a regression model, we need to asses the preformance of the predictive mode (e.g.model_1) and evaluate how well the model is in predicting the outcome of a new test data(e.g.testdata).

#percentage of error for model_1 (23%)

sigma(model_1)*100/mean(cdata$Crime)
## [1] 23.09887

Building a second model(model_2) with fewer predictors

#let’s look at how graphically these variables are correlated

ggpairs(cdata, columns = c("Crime","M", "Ed", "Po1", "So","Ineq","Prob"))

Comparing to the predicted value of a crime we got from model_1, this one is a much better prediction and within the range of our data. However, how much better is it? some calculations below shows that RMSE only improved a bit from 209 to 200, and percentage of error is 22% down by only 1% from 23% calculated for model_1.

Also, the R2, and F-stat still look good with the significant predictors. Overall we are now more confidence that the second model is better than the first one. Not necessary for this assignment, but wanted to explore application of our findings above on the training/test set [please skip if it bores you]:

To build a predictive regression model: 1.Randomly split the data into training_set(80%)and test_set(20%) 2.Building the regression model using the training set 3.Making prediction using the test set, and compute the model accuracy metrics

test_set=subset(cdata, split==FALSE)
